00:00:00.072 --> 00:00:01.530
AMANDA BRENNAN: A
lot of my work is

00:00:01.530 --> 00:00:05.720
focused on keeping on the pulse
of trends of internet culture.

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:07.520
My name is Amanda Brennan.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:10.730
And I'm a Content and
Community Associate at Tumblr.

00:00:10.730 --> 00:00:12.335
I am also a meme librarian.

00:00:15.570 --> 00:00:17.770
A meme is a piece
of content that

00:00:17.770 --> 00:00:21.410
travels from person to person
and changes along the way.

00:00:21.410 --> 00:00:25.790
The term was coined in 1976 by
evolutionary biologist Richard

00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:28.110
Dawkins in his book
"The Selfish Gene."

00:00:28.110 --> 00:00:29.690
He originally used
it to describe

00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:33.220
pieces of cultural
transmission, so stuff

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:36.490
like melodies or catchphrases,
even trends in fashion.

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:43.360
Before the internet, memes still
came in all shapes and sizes.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:46.780
One of the earliest
instances is Kilroy Was Here.

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:50.470
It's this piece of graffiti that
was popularized in World War II

00:00:50.470 --> 00:00:51.730
by American soldiers.

00:00:51.730 --> 00:00:53.679
So when new soldiers
came through,

00:00:53.679 --> 00:00:55.470
they knew that their
people had been there.

00:00:58.510 --> 00:01:00.620
Another one that's
a great example

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:02.660
is the Star Wars opening crawl.

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:05.250
It's been used in
parodies since two years

00:01:05.250 --> 00:01:09.370
after the original
film was released.

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:11.900
Internet memes can take
many different forms still.

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:14.430
They can be hashtags, emoticons.

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:16.210
They could be a video or a vine.

00:01:16.210 --> 00:01:17.985
Songs can be memes.

00:01:17.985 --> 00:01:20.630
What lives solely
in internet space

00:01:20.630 --> 00:01:23.060
can sometimes be very
fleeting or temporal.

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:25.130
Flash animations
like Homestar Runner

00:01:25.130 --> 00:01:26.970
were huge in the early 2000s.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:30.770
2005 marked the birth of
YouTube and every video meme.

00:01:30.770 --> 00:01:32.520
BRIAN COLLINS: And
boom goes the dynamite.

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:34.600
AMANDA BRENNAN: In
2009, we really thought

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:37.270
about stereotypes
and representing them

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:41.040
online in stuff like Advice
Animals and Rage Comics.

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:43.910
2013, we changed
language with doge.

00:01:43.910 --> 00:01:46.220
Dogs were assigned
their own dialect,

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:48.633
just like cats were
in the early 2000s.

