00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:56.080
Memes had a longer life
span a few years ago.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.300
Now, we see memes like
"If a Dog Wore Pants."

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:00.370
It got super big.

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:01.990
It appeared on the "Today Show."

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:05.130
But after a few days, no one
was really talking about it.

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:07.820
It's so important
right now to be

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:11.020
archiving this stuff because
meme culture is really

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:12.540
rapidly growing.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:15.350
And it represents what's
going on the outskirts of pop

00:02:15.350 --> 00:02:16.160
culture.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.230
We can learn so much about
how people communicate

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:21.290
through internet memes.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:23.660
We also really learn
about communities.

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:27.600
There's a series of blogs called
"What Should We Call Me" where

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:29.890
people will change
it a little bit

00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:32.570
to be about their profession
or their locality.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:34.570
And using the
reaction gifs, they

00:02:34.570 --> 00:02:37.710
can identify their
feelings and share it

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:41.220
within a community that
knows how they feel.

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:42.600
Memes are fun.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:44.500
And they're really cool.

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:47.560
And it's a way to sometimes
work through hard stuff.

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:50.330
It adds more nuance to
speech and interaction.

00:02:50.330 --> 00:02:52.550
We have no idea how
people were really

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:56.290
sharing their weird cultural
ideas before the internet.

00:02:56.290 --> 00:02:59.050
Now, someone can tweet
something and someone

00:02:59.050 --> 00:03:02.342
across the globe can
identify with it.

